 Here's a possible implementation of a program to find the common elements in two arrays without using any extra data structures:
```
function commonElements(arr1, arr2) {
  let result = [];
  for (let i = 0; i < arr1.length; i++) {
    for (let j = 0; j < arr2.length; j++) {
      if (arr1[i] === arr2[j]) {
        result.push(arr2[j]);
      }
    }
  }
  return result;
}
```
This function takes two arrays as input and returns an array of the common elements found in both arrays. It does this by iterating over the elements of both arrays and checking if an element in the first array is equal to an element in the second array. If an element is found, it is pushed onto the result array.

Here is an example of how this function would be used:
```
const arr1 = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
const arr2 = [4, 5, 6];
console.log(commonElements(arr1, arr2)); // Output: [4, 5]
```
This function has a time complexity of O(n^2) because it iterates over the elements of both arrays twice.

Please note that this solution does not handle the case where one of the arrays is empty, so you should add a check for that before the loop.

